1
00:03:29,490 --> 00:03:32,393
This was my body.

2
00:03:42,169 --> 00:03:45,873
On December 27, 1979,

3
00:03:45,907 --> 00:03:48,542
I lay in bed all day.

4
00:03:48,575 --> 00:03:52,246
Whether I was asleep or in a coma

5
00:03:52,279 --> 00:03:55,082
later became a subject of dispute.

6
00:03:58,252 --> 00:04:00,254
When my breathing
became obstructed...

7
00:04:00,922 --> 00:04:01,923
Maria.

8
00:04:01,956 --> 00:04:05,392
My husband, Claus von Bulow,

9
00:04:05,426 --> 00:04:09,463
finally did as my maid
had been urging all day.

10
00:04:09,496 --> 00:04:11,498
He summoned a physician.

11
00:04:11,532 --> 00:04:13,000
Dr Paultees?

12
00:04:13,034 --> 00:04:17,905
I stopped breathing. My
heart stopped beating.

13
00:04:17,939 --> 00:04:21,408
By this time, I was
certainly in a deep coma

14
00:04:21,442 --> 00:04:25,179
from which I awoke
several hours later.

15
00:04:25,212 --> 00:04:28,582
By the next morning,
I was myself again.

16
00:04:28,615 --> 00:04:31,986
There's no reason
for all this fuss.

17
00:04:32,019 --> 00:04:34,088
I never felt better
in my whole life.

18
00:04:34,121 --> 00:04:37,358
This first coma aroused
suspicion and fear

19
00:04:37,391 --> 00:04:40,828
in the minds of my
personal maid Maria,

20
00:04:40,962 --> 00:04:44,966
my son Alex, and my
elder daughter Ala.

21
00:04:44,999 --> 00:04:47,432
From this time on,
though they never

22
00:04:47,433 --> 00:04:49,470
voiced their suspicions to me,

23
00:04:49,503 --> 00:04:52,539
they kept a vigilant eye on Claus.

24
00:04:53,574 --> 00:04:55,109
A year later,

25
00:04:55,142 --> 00:04:56,844
just before Christmas,

26
00:04:56,878 --> 00:04:59,981
their darkest fears
seemed justified.

27
00:05:00,014 --> 00:05:03,817
- Has Mummy had breakfast yet?
- No, we haven't seen her.

28
00:05:19,400 --> 00:05:21,551
My husband did not
want our daughter

29
00:05:21,552 --> 00:05:23,470
Cosima to see what he had found,

30
00:05:23,504 --> 00:05:26,107
so he motioned to
his stepson Alex.

31
00:05:41,055 --> 00:05:44,892
Second coma. My pulse was 38,

32
00:05:45,059 --> 00:05:48,429
my temperature 81.6 degrees.

33
00:05:51,198 --> 00:05:53,534
Did you call an ambulance?

34
00:05:55,369 --> 00:05:58,005
Nicholas, would you ask Robert
to open the main gates.

35
00:05:58,039 --> 00:06:01,008
We're expecting an ambulance.

36
00:06:01,042 --> 00:06:04,378
Send an ambulance immediately...

37
00:06:04,411 --> 00:06:06,613
- Keep her in something warm.
- Thank you.

38
00:06:06,647 --> 00:06:08,682
Oh, a blanket or
anything you can find.

39
00:06:08,715 --> 00:06:12,186
All this activity was pointless.

40
00:06:13,554 --> 00:06:14,922
We'd better do an EEG.

41
00:06:15,056 --> 00:06:17,224
I never woke from this coma,

42
00:06:17,258 --> 00:06:18,559
and I never will.

43
00:06:20,427 --> 00:06:24,932
I am what doctors call "persistent
vegetative", a vegetable.

44
00:06:27,301 --> 00:06:30,040
According to medical
experts, I could

45
00:06:30,041 --> 00:06:32,706
stay like this for
a very long time,

46
00:06:32,739 --> 00:06:36,077
brain-dead, body better than ever.

47
00:06:38,112 --> 00:06:43,951
Enter Robert Brillhoffer, former
Manhattan district attorney.

48
00:06:43,985 --> 00:06:46,105
My two children from my first

49
00:06:46,106 --> 00:06:48,956
marriage, Alex and
Ala von Auersberg,

50
00:06:48,990 --> 00:06:51,925
hired Brillhoffer to
investigate the case.

51
00:06:53,760 --> 00:06:57,398
He put a "do not resuscitate"
order on her hospital chart.

52
00:06:57,431 --> 00:07:00,334
They sent Alex and a
private investigator

53
00:07:00,367 --> 00:07:03,575
back to my Newport
cottage, Clarendon

54
00:07:03,576 --> 00:07:05,939
Court, to search for drugs.

55
00:07:08,542 --> 00:07:12,980
They found plenty,
in Claus's closet.

56
00:07:13,147 --> 00:07:15,749
On top of that, the
hospital lab reported

57
00:07:15,782 --> 00:07:21,022
that my blood insulin on
admission was 14 times normal,

58
00:07:21,055 --> 00:07:25,592
a level almost surely
caused by injection.

59
00:07:25,626 --> 00:07:29,063
Insulin injection could
readily cause coma...

60
00:07:30,464 --> 00:07:32,066
Or death.

61
00:07:34,035 --> 00:07:37,971
This encrusted needle tested
positive for insulin.

62
00:07:39,340 --> 00:07:43,477
Alex couldn't wait to get
back and show Brillhoffer.

63
00:07:44,645 --> 00:07:47,181
Now they felt they had
the murder weapon.

64
00:07:47,214 --> 00:07:50,351
All they lacked was the motive.

65
00:07:50,384 --> 00:07:54,021
At that moment, my husband was
vacationing with his mistress,

66
00:07:54,088 --> 00:07:58,725
the very beautiful soap-opera
actress, Alexandra Isles.

67
00:07:59,093 --> 00:08:00,327
Oh, God.

68
00:08:00,361 --> 00:08:02,563
Mrs Isles, a divorcee,

69
00:08:02,596 --> 00:08:06,200
was the daughter of an old
friend, Count Billy Botsky.

70
00:08:09,770 --> 00:08:13,040
Brillhoffer also discovered
that, at my death,

71
00:08:13,207 --> 00:08:17,244
Claus, whose own net worth
was only a million dollars,

72
00:08:17,278 --> 00:08:21,215
stood to inherit 14
million from me.

73
00:08:21,248 --> 00:08:24,310
Alexandra later
testified that Claus

74
00:08:24,311 --> 00:08:27,621
showed her a legal
analysis of my will.

75
00:08:29,290 --> 00:08:34,695
On the evidence collected by Alex,
Ala and their lawyer Brillhoffer,

76
00:08:34,728 --> 00:08:37,087
my husband was accused
of twice trying

77
00:08:37,088 --> 00:08:39,566
to murder me with
injections of insulin.

78
00:08:40,534 --> 00:08:43,770
On March 16, 1982,

79
00:08:43,804 --> 00:08:47,108
he was found guilty
on both counts.

80
00:08:47,141 --> 00:08:49,510
Committed on December 27, 1979...

81
00:08:49,543 --> 00:08:53,614
Even Alexandra Isles
testified against him.

82
00:08:53,647 --> 00:08:55,082
Guilty.

83
00:08:55,216 --> 00:08:56,383
As to count two,

84
00:08:56,417 --> 00:08:59,853
charged the defendant committed
on December 21, 1980,

85
00:08:59,886 --> 00:09:02,089
a crime of assault
with intent to murder.

86
00:09:02,223 --> 00:09:03,857
- How do you find?
- Guilty.

87
00:09:03,890 --> 00:09:08,295
You are about to see how Claus
von Bulow sought to reverse

88
00:09:08,329 --> 00:09:11,398
or escape from that
jury's verdict.

89
00:09:12,766 --> 00:09:14,801
You tell me.

90
00:09:20,774 --> 00:09:22,276
And two.

91
00:09:22,309 --> 00:09:26,079
Here it comes. Here we go, taking
you downtown. And Dersh...

92
00:09:27,481 --> 00:09:31,785
Take it in. Foul. Okay, here I go.

93
00:09:31,818 --> 00:09:34,521
Watch the hands. Watch the hands.

94
00:09:40,261 --> 00:09:41,662
Yeah, hello.

95
00:09:42,496 --> 00:09:44,131
What?

96
00:09:46,667 --> 00:09:49,102
Oh, shit. Bottom line.

97
00:09:49,836 --> 00:09:51,104
Aw, shit.

98
00:10:12,326 --> 00:10:14,127
Hi.

99
00:10:20,301 --> 00:10:23,304
Let's try that again. Hi,
Dad. Remember Maggie?

100
00:10:24,571 --> 00:10:26,673
Hi, Maggie.

101
00:10:28,909 --> 00:10:32,446
They're gonna fry. The
Johnson brothers.

102
00:10:32,479 --> 00:10:35,216
What? But...

103
00:10:37,318 --> 00:10:40,287
Two black kids broke their
father out of prison.

104
00:10:40,321 --> 00:10:43,324
The father shot two people and the
sons are convicted of murder.

105
00:10:43,357 --> 00:10:45,559
A lawyer prays for
an innocent client.

106
00:10:45,592 --> 00:10:49,196
Finally, finally, I get two. Both
of them are gonna get zapped.

107
00:10:49,330 --> 00:10:50,330
No more appeals?

108
00:10:50,331 --> 00:10:51,798
Supreme Court but, this
was the best shot.

109
00:10:53,934 --> 00:10:56,537
Whoa. It's the press.

110
00:10:56,570 --> 00:10:58,672
You don't want to
talk to the press?

111
00:11:00,374 --> 00:11:03,610
Dershowitz Psychiatric Institute.

112
00:11:04,245 --> 00:11:06,213
Yeah, hang on a second.

113
00:11:06,247 --> 00:11:08,749
Claus von Bulow.

114
00:11:08,782 --> 00:11:12,653
- It's a reporter.
- With an English accent?

115
00:11:12,686 --> 00:11:15,489
What paper do you represent?

116
00:11:15,522 --> 00:11:16,923
If I can't save two innocent kids,

117
00:11:16,957 --> 00:11:18,491
what's the point? They
might as well hang them.

118
00:11:18,492 --> 00:11:20,361
Yeah, one second. Sorry.

119
00:11:20,394 --> 00:11:22,596
He really seems to
think he's von Bulow.

120
00:11:22,629 --> 00:11:24,231
Hello. This is Alan Dershowitz.

121
00:11:24,265 --> 00:11:25,866
Who are you? What do you want?

122
00:11:30,404 --> 00:11:33,374
- It is von Bulow.
- Back in business.

123
00:11:40,046 --> 00:11:42,249
- Can I help you, sir?
- Claus von Bulow?

124
00:11:42,283 --> 00:11:44,251
Elevators to the left.

125
00:11:51,558 --> 00:11:53,560
Holy shit.

126
00:12:00,934 --> 00:12:02,936
Hello?

127
00:12:08,609 --> 00:12:10,711
Hello?

128
00:12:10,744 --> 00:12:14,715
Professor Dershowitz.
Hello, hello.

129
00:12:14,748 --> 00:12:18,051
- How good of you to come.
- Pleasure.

130
00:12:18,084 --> 00:12:20,253
Won't you sit down?

131
00:12:27,461 --> 00:12:30,263
- Do you play?
- That? No.

132
00:12:31,432 --> 00:12:34,067
Most people think
it's a game of luck.

133
00:12:34,100 --> 00:12:36,603
Actually, it's largely
a matter of nerve.

134
00:12:42,609 --> 00:12:44,811
Nothing, thank you, Charles.

135
00:12:44,845 --> 00:12:48,915
Why don't we go to Delmonico's
and have a proper lunch?

136
00:12:48,949 --> 00:12:50,451
Whatever.

137
00:12:54,355 --> 00:12:56,590
I should tell you, that I
have the greatest respect

138
00:12:56,623 --> 00:12:59,793
for the intelligence and
integrity of the Jewish people.

139
00:13:03,530 --> 00:13:05,166
When I married Sunny, she was the

140
00:13:05,167 --> 00:13:07,100
most beautiful
divorcee in the world,

141
00:13:07,133 --> 00:13:08,969
and one of the wealthiest.

142
00:13:09,002 --> 00:13:12,673
Even so, we never got this table.

143
00:13:12,706 --> 00:13:14,741
Professor Dershowitz.

144
00:13:17,511 --> 00:13:19,880
Dr von Bulow.

145
00:13:19,913 --> 00:13:22,849
Two injections of insulin,
already I'm a doctor.

146
00:13:22,883 --> 00:13:26,353
In America, it's fame
rather than class.

147
00:13:26,520 --> 00:13:29,856
Now, after all this
unpleasantness,

148
00:13:29,890 --> 00:13:32,058
I always get the best table.

149
00:13:33,727 --> 00:13:35,061
Speaking of the unpleasantness...

150
00:13:35,095 --> 00:13:37,898
Oh, yes. We'd better
discuss your fee.

151
00:13:39,600 --> 00:13:42,703
Okay. $300 an hour.

152
00:13:43,570 --> 00:13:46,072
Good Lord.

153
00:13:46,106 --> 00:13:48,409
You know, I used to be
a lawyer in London.

154
00:13:48,442 --> 00:13:49,910
That sounds a bit steep.

155
00:13:49,943 --> 00:13:51,812
It's average for a case like this.

156
00:13:51,845 --> 00:13:54,080
Besides, I do a lot
of pro Bono work.

157
00:13:54,114 --> 00:13:57,384
You'd pay for that. Plus, I have
to pay students, associates.

158
00:13:57,418 --> 00:14:00,123
Are you saying that if I agree to

159
00:14:00,124 --> 00:14:03,156
pay 300, you will
handle my appeal?

160
00:14:03,189 --> 00:14:06,527
No, not so far. Doesn't
look like my kind of case.

161
00:14:08,061 --> 00:14:09,863
I'm not a hired gun.

162
00:14:09,896 --> 00:14:12,533
I gotta feel that some moral or
constitutional issue is at stake.

163
00:14:12,566 --> 00:14:15,168
But I'm absolutely innocent.

164
00:14:15,201 --> 00:14:19,406
And my civil liberties have
been egregiously violated.

165
00:14:19,473 --> 00:14:21,425
Two black kids are
facing the electric

166
00:14:21,426 --> 00:14:23,376
chair for a crime
they did not commit.

167
00:14:24,545 --> 00:14:26,379
They are innocent.

168
00:14:28,048 --> 00:14:32,419
Well, before you assume I'm
guilty, won't you hear my story?

169
00:14:32,586 --> 00:14:34,721
No. Never let defendants explain.

170
00:14:34,755 --> 00:14:36,723
Puts most of them in
an awkward position.

171
00:14:37,624 --> 00:14:40,393
- How do you mean?
- Lying.

172
00:14:42,463 --> 00:14:44,831
But I give you my
word as a gentleman.

173
00:14:46,132 --> 00:14:48,569
Oh. Well...

174
00:14:52,673 --> 00:14:58,479
Won't you at least read the record
and see if you can find something

175
00:15:00,681 --> 00:15:01,915
constitutional?

176
00:15:04,785 --> 00:15:07,020
You do have one thing
in your favour.

177
00:15:09,523 --> 00:15:10,523
Everybody hates you.

178
00:15:16,997 --> 00:15:19,466
Well, that's a start.

179
00:15:19,533 --> 00:15:22,503
Come on, Maxwell.
Yeah. Come on, Max.

180
00:15:22,536 --> 00:15:24,771
- It was a hit.
- Yes.

181
00:15:28,509 --> 00:15:31,244
- So, what do you think?
- Oh, he did it. He did it.

182
00:15:31,277 --> 00:15:33,480
Of course he did it. Can we win?

183
00:15:33,614 --> 00:15:35,482
A hundred to one
against. The maid...

184
00:15:35,616 --> 00:15:37,515
The maid schmeared him on both

185
00:15:37,516 --> 00:15:39,920
comas. Look at this.
It says here...

186
00:15:39,953 --> 00:15:43,256
After you realised that Mrs.
Von Bulow had not gotten up,

187
00:15:43,289 --> 00:15:44,491
what did you do?

188
00:15:44,625 --> 00:15:46,760
I came downstairs,

189
00:15:46,793 --> 00:15:51,264
and Mr von Bulow said that
Madame had a very sore throat,

190
00:15:51,297 --> 00:15:53,834
and I didn't have to do any work,

191
00:15:53,867 --> 00:15:56,469
and she was in bed all day.

192
00:16:07,681 --> 00:16:11,484
What are you doing?
Did we ring for you?

193
00:16:19,059 --> 00:16:21,628
She's ice-cold.

194
00:16:21,662 --> 00:16:24,030
Madame. Mrs von Bulow.

195
00:16:24,064 --> 00:16:27,968
Leave her alone. She's sleeping.

196
00:16:28,001 --> 00:16:30,537
She was drinking last night.
We didn't get any rest.

197
00:16:30,571 --> 00:16:32,038
She's not sleeping.

198
00:16:33,774 --> 00:16:35,508
She's unconscious.

199
00:16:36,276 --> 00:16:39,512
- You must call a doctor.
- Maria.

200
00:16:41,281 --> 00:16:42,883
Go on.

201
00:16:52,593 --> 00:16:55,195
A half-hour later,
she had not moved.

202
00:16:55,228 --> 00:16:57,998
I went back and forth all morning.

203
00:17:00,033 --> 00:17:04,605
Finally, mid-afternoon, Mr von
Bulow spoke to Dr Paultees.

204
00:17:05,238 --> 00:17:07,708
But he lied to doctor.

205
00:17:07,741 --> 00:17:09,576
Yes, she's sleeping now,
but she was up earlier

206
00:17:09,610 --> 00:17:12,278
this morning to the bathroom
and had a soft drink,

207
00:17:12,312 --> 00:17:14,581
so I don't think, there's
any cause for alarm...

208
00:17:14,715 --> 00:17:18,585
But she never moved. Never got up.

209
00:17:18,719 --> 00:17:22,856
She was lying in the
same position all day.

210
00:17:22,889 --> 00:17:26,793
Later her heart stops, and Dr
Paultees, he comes and saves her.

211
00:17:28,294 --> 00:17:31,598
After they go to the hospital,
I'm changing the sheets.

212
00:17:31,632 --> 00:17:34,300
I find a puddle of urine.

213
00:17:34,334 --> 00:17:36,036
If Madame went to the bathroom,

214
00:17:36,069 --> 00:17:38,739
she would not have
peed in her bed.

215
00:17:38,772 --> 00:17:41,708
Right. Why would Claus
lie about that?

216
00:17:41,742 --> 00:17:45,045
Well, it's suspicious
but hardly criminal.

217
00:17:45,078 --> 00:17:46,613
How about the second coma?

218
00:17:46,647 --> 00:17:49,616
Oh, Maria wasn't in
Newport for that one.

219
00:17:49,683 --> 00:17:50,984
But shortly before
the second coma...

220
00:17:51,017 --> 00:17:52,619
I'm cleaning up their room

221
00:17:52,686 --> 00:17:55,121
when I find Mr von
Bulow's white canvas bag

222
00:17:55,155 --> 00:17:57,123
packed for Newport.

223
00:17:57,157 --> 00:18:00,627
Inside, there's a
little black bag.

224
00:18:00,794 --> 00:18:04,297
A bottle of insulin, a
syringe and needles.

225
00:18:04,330 --> 00:18:07,100
Alexander. Alexander, come here.

226
00:18:10,771 --> 00:18:12,038
Insulin?

227
00:18:13,139 --> 00:18:17,110
For what, insulin? My
lady's not diabetic.

228
00:18:22,783 --> 00:18:25,919
Three weeks later, Sunny's
lying unconscious

229
00:18:25,952 --> 00:18:29,823
in a freezing bathroom with her
nightgown hiked over her waist.

230
00:18:29,856 --> 00:18:32,192
If I was on that jury, I
would've voted to convict.

231
00:18:32,959 --> 00:18:35,662
Then you're taking the case?

232
00:18:35,729 --> 00:18:37,864
Reminds me of my Hitler dream.

233
00:18:39,065 --> 00:18:42,669
Hitler calls up, he's
alive, needs a lawyer.

234
00:18:42,836 --> 00:18:46,272
I say "Sure. Come on over."

235
00:18:46,306 --> 00:18:49,676
Then I have to decide do I take
the case or do I kill him?

236
00:18:49,710 --> 00:18:52,012
You? No question.

237
00:18:52,045 --> 00:18:54,647
- I would take the case.
- Then kill him.

238
00:18:56,316 --> 00:18:58,719
I'm a maniac. I need someone
with your judgement,

239
00:18:58,752 --> 00:19:00,120
someone to watch what I'm doing

240
00:19:00,153 --> 00:19:02,789
and occasionally remind
me about the law.

241
00:19:02,823 --> 00:19:04,691
When can I see the transcripts?

242
00:19:04,825 --> 00:19:08,695
You're a former prosecutor,
conservative. We agree on nothing.

243
00:19:08,829 --> 00:19:10,196
But you're smarter
than Rhode Island DA.

244
00:19:10,230 --> 00:19:13,366
If I can beat your arguments,
I can destroy his.

245
00:19:13,399 --> 00:19:15,702
Look, Rhode Island is the most
corrupt state in the country.

246
00:19:15,736 --> 00:19:16,903
Everything is political.

247
00:19:16,937 --> 00:19:18,972
I don't think that way. You do.

248
00:19:19,005 --> 00:19:20,781
I have to see the big
picture. I can't

249
00:19:20,782 --> 00:19:22,375
afford to immerse myself in facts.

250
00:19:22,408 --> 00:19:24,410
But we must know the facts.

251
00:19:24,444 --> 00:19:26,880
Out of all my ex-students,
no one can assimilate

252
00:19:26,913 --> 00:19:28,715
information as quickly as you two.

253
00:19:28,882 --> 00:19:30,784
